Peak Progression Analysis

Model the seasonal progression of the latitudinal peak in zooplankton carbon and net primary production.

Objectives:

  • Extract peak latitude for each day (2005-2024)
  • Visualize peak progression over time
  • Determine when peak is furthest south (ecological year boundary)
  • Model peak latitude as monotonically increasing function within each year

In[5]:
# Find peak latitude for each day
print("Finding peak latitudes for each day...")

peak_data = []

for i in range(len(ds.time)):
    date = pd.Timestamp(ds.time.isel(time=i).values)
    
    # ZOOC peak
    zooc_profile = zooc_lon_mean.isel(time=i)
    zooc_peak_idx = zooc_profile.argmax().values
    zooc_peak_lat = ds.latitude.isel(latitude=zooc_peak_idx).values
    zooc_peak_val = zooc_profile.isel(latitude=zooc_peak_idx).values
    
    # NPP peak
    npp_profile = npp_lon_mean.isel(time=i)
    npp_peak_idx = npp_profile.argmax().values
    npp_peak_lat = ds.latitude.isel(latitude=npp_peak_idx).values
    npp_peak_val = npp_profile.isel(latitude=npp_peak_idx).values
    
    peak_data.append({
        'date': date,
        'year': date.year,
        'month': date.month,
        'day': date.day,
        'dayofyear': date.dayofyear,
        'zooc_peak_lat': zooc_peak_lat,
        'zooc_peak_val': zooc_peak_val,
        'npp_peak_lat': npp_peak_lat,
        'npp_peak_val': npp_peak_val
    })

# Create DataFrame
peaks_df = pd.DataFrame(peak_data)
print(f"Extracted peaks for {len(peaks_df)} days")
peaks_df.head()

5. Find Ecological Year Boundary (Peak Furthest South)

In[8]:
# Find when peak is furthest south on average
# Use rolling mean to smooth out daily variability
window = 30  # 30-day rolling mean

zooc_smooth = seasonal_mean_zooc.rolling(window=window, center=True).mean()
npp_smooth = seasonal_mean_npp.rolling(window=window, center=True).mean()

zooc_min_day = zooc_smooth.idxmin()
npp_min_day = npp_smooth.idxmin()

print(f"ZOOC peak furthest south: Day {zooc_min_day} ({pd.Timestamp('2024-01-01') + pd.Timedelta(days=int(zooc_min_day)-1):%B %d})")
print(f"NPP peak furthest south: Day {npp_min_day} ({pd.Timestamp('2024-01-01') + pd.Timedelta(days=int(npp_min_day)-1):%B %d})")

print(f"  ZOOC: {zooc_smooth.min():.2f}N")
print(f"  NPP: {npp_smooth.min():.2f}N")

6. Check Monotonicity Assumption

In[10]:
# For each variable, check if peak generally increases within ecological year
# Use the minimum from smoothed data as year boundary

def assign_ecological_year(row, year_start_day):
    """Assign ecological year based on year start day."""
    if row['dayofyear'] >= year_start_day:
        return row['year']
    else:
        return row['year'] - 1

# Assign ecological years
peaks_df['eco_year_zooc'] = peaks_df.apply(lambda r: assign_ecological_year(r, zooc_min_day), axis=1)
peaks_df['eco_year_npp'] = peaks_df.apply(lambda r: assign_ecological_year(r, npp_min_day), axis=1)

# Calculate day within ecological year
peaks_df['eco_dayofyear_zooc'] = peaks_df.apply(
    lambda r: (r['dayofyear'] - zooc_min_day) % 365, axis=1
)
peaks_df['eco_dayofyear_npp'] = peaks_df.apply(
    lambda r: (r['dayofyear'] - npp_min_day) % 365, axis=1
)

print("Ecological years assigned!")
print(f"ZOOC ecological years: {peaks_df['eco_year_zooc'].min()} to {peaks_df['eco_year_zooc'].max()}")
print(f"NPP ecological years: {peaks_df['eco_year_npp'].min()} to {peaks_df['eco_year_npp'].max()}")

Ecological years assigned!
ZOOC ecological years: 2004 to 2024
NPP ecological years: 2004 to 2024

# Prepare data for modeling
# Use ecological day of year and ecological year

# ZOOC model data
X_zooc = peaks_df[['eco_dayofyear_zooc', 'eco_year_zooc']].values
y_zooc = peaks_df['zooc_peak_lat'].values

# NPP model data  
X_npp = peaks_df[['eco_dayofyear_npp', 'eco_year_npp']].values
y_npp = peaks_df['npp_peak_lat'].values

print(f"ZOOC data: {X_zooc.shape}, {y_zooc.shape}")
print(f"NPP data: {X_npp.shape}, {y_npp.shape}")

ZOOC data: (7305, 2), (7305,)
NPP data: (7305, 2), (7305,)
In[]:
# Fit GAM for ZOOC with monotonic increasing constraint
# s() creates a smooth spline term for continuous variables
# f() creates a factor term for categorical variables (random effect)
# constraints='monotonic_inc' ensures peak latitude increases with day of year
print("Fitting ZOOC GAM model with monotonic constraint...")
gam_zooc = LinearGAM(s(0, n_splines=25, constraints='monotonic_inc') + f(1))  # s(dayofyear) + f(year)
gam_zooc.gridsearch(X_zooc, y_zooc)

print(f"ZOOC GAM fitted!")
print(f"  Pseudo R: {gam_zooc.statistics_['pseudo_r2']['explained_deviance']:.4f}")
print(f"  AIC: {gam_zooc.statistics_['AIC']:.2f}")
print(f"  Number of splines: {gam_zooc.terms[0].n_splines}")
In[]:

In[18]:
# For each latitude band, find when the peak occurs during the year
# Average across years to get the typical timing

print("Computing timing of peak for each latitude band...")

# Get the longitudinal means we already computed
# Shape: (time, latitude)
zooc_profiles = zooc_lon_mean.values
npp_profiles = npp_lon_mean.values

# For each latitude, find the day of year when peak occurs
latitudes = ds.latitude.values
n_lats = len(latitudes)

# Get day of year for each time step
dates = pd.DatetimeIndex(ds.time.values)
dayofyear_array = np.array([d.dayofyear for d in dates])

# Average across years - reshape to (n_years, 365/366, n_lats)
# For simplicity, work with full time series and find argmax

zooc_peak_timing = np.zeros(n_lats)
npp_peak_timing = np.zeros(n_lats)

for i in range(n_lats):
    # Get time series for this latitude
    zooc_ts = zooc_profiles[:, i]
    npp_ts = npp_profiles[:, i]
    
    # Find index of maximum
    zooc_max_idx = np.argmax(zooc_ts)
    npp_max_idx = np.argmax(npp_ts)
    
    # Get day of year
    zooc_peak_timing[i] = dayofyear_array[zooc_max_idx]
    npp_peak_timing[i] = dayofyear_array[npp_max_idx]

print("Done!")

Computing timing of peak for each latitude band...
